Copy
Edit
sequenceDiagram
autonumber
participant Client
participant Loop as EventLoop
participant Conn as ClientConnection
participant Parser as RequestParser
participant Router
participant H as Handler
participant CGI as CgiProcess

Client->>Loop: connect()
Loop->>Conn: accept() -> new fd
loop poll()
  Loop->>Conn: onReadable()
  Conn->>Parser: feed(bytes)
  Parser-->>Conn: headers/body complete?
  alt request complete
    Conn->>Router: resolve(req)
    Router-->>H: pick StaticHandler | CgiHandler
    alt StaticHandler
      H-->>Conn: build HttpResponse (file/autoindex)
    else CGI
      H->>CGI: spawn + env + body
      CGI-->>H: headers+body (EOF)
      H-->>Conn: build HttpResponse
    end
    Conn->>Loop: want WRITE
    Loop->>Conn: onWritable()
    Conn-->>Client: send response
    alt keep-alive
      Conn->>Parser: reset(); state=RECV_HEADERS
    else close
      Conn->>Loop: remove FD; state=CLOSED
    end
  end
end


Why this is better for 42 webserv
Focuses on required features only: GET/POST/DELETE, uploads, multi-ports, CGI, default error pages, single non-blocking loop.

Adds an explicit connection state machine and deadlines (requests must not hang).

Keeps parsing incremental (RequestParser separate from HttpRequest).

Keeps CGI clean: a registry by extension, a process wrapper, and the handler that translates to/from HTTP.

What we intentionally removed
Reverse proxy, upstream pools, balancers, sessions/cookies management, rate limits, PUT/PATCH, ETag/CRC helpers. They’re cool, but out-of-scope and time sinks.
